  "prompt": "After demonetization of Rs.500 and Rs.1000 notes, what will happen to old notes?",
  "response": "After the demonetization of Rs. 500 and Rs. 1000 notes, the old notes that were rendered invalid for regular transactions could be deposited into banks or exchanged for new notes within a specified period. The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) and other authorized banks facilitated this process. After the deadline for deposits and exchanges, the old notes were no longer accepted as legal tender and essentially became worthless for transactions. \n\nThe collected old notes were then processed by the RBI. Typically, these notes were shredded and disposed of in a secure manner to ensure they could not re-enter circulation. Some of the shredded notes might be recycled or repurposed for other uses, such as in the production of various products, including stationery items or fuel, depending on the policies and capabilities of the RBI and associated organizations.",
